\textcolor{red}{磁矩}

The magnitude of the flux density can be defined by the mechanical torque $\vec{N}$ exerted on the magnetic dipole:
\begin{equation}
\vec{N} = \vec{\mu} \times \vec{B}
\end{equation}
where $\vec{\mu}$ is the magnetic moment of the dipole.

\subsection{Biot and Savart Law}
If $\dif \vec{l}$ is an element of length (pointing in the direction of current flow) of a filamentary wire that carries a current $\vec{I}$ and $\vec{x}$ is the coordinate vector from the element of length to an observation point P, then the elemental flux density $\dif \vec{B}$ at the point P is given in magnitude and direction by
\begin{equation}
\dif \vec{B} = k I \frac{(\dif \vec{l} \times \vec{x})}{|\vec{x}|^3}
\end{equation}




















